{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585959"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:23:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:23:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15041"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15041"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.04,0.3,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116270"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7729"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15041"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98266"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18878"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18881"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116270"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERhabdomyolysis results in the release of myoglobin from damaged skeletal muscle into the circulation. This protein can cause acute kidney injury through several mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how myoglobin causes renal tubular damage in rhabdomyolysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Causes direct oxidative damage to tubular cells","Forms clear hyaline casts","Stimulates inflammatory cytokine release","Increases tubular sodium reabsorption","Causes vasodilation of afferent arterioles"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn rhabdomyolysis, myoglobin damages the kidney through three main mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect oxidative damage to tubular cells\u003C/strong\u003E through free radical generation and lipid peroxidation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFormation of dark pigmented casts that obstruct tubules\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EVasoconstriction leading to reduced renal blood flow and ischaemia\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMyoglobin \u003Cstrong\u003Eforms clear hyaline casts\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as myoglobin forms dark pigmented casts, not clear casts. \u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates inflammatory cytokine release\u003C/strong\u003E is not a primary mechanism, although inflammation may occur. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases tubular sodium reabsorption\u003C/strong\u003E is not a direct effect of myoglobin on renal tubules. \u003Cstrong\u003ECauses vasodilation of afferent arterioles\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because myoglobin causes vasoconstriction, not vasodilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of these mechanisms leads to acute tubular necrosis and acute kidney injury in rhabdomyolysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Myoglobin causes renal damage through direct tubular toxicity, cast formation, and vasoconstriction","Myoglobin forms dark pigmented casts, not clear casts, in renal tubules","Myoglobin causes vasoconstriction, not vasodilation, leading to reduced renal blood flow"],"references":["Mendes P, Robles PG, Mathur S. Statin-induced rhabdomyolysis: a comprehensive review of case reports. Physiother Can. 2014 Spring;66(2):124-32. doi: 10.3138/ptc.2012-65. PMID: 24799748; PMCID: PMC4006404","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98266"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15041"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98266"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T03:34:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T03:34:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7729"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116270"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":nul